==Chinese==
{{zh-forms|s=岁|alt=嵗,亗,㞸,㱑,歳,𡻕,𫞓,𢧡,𢧁,𭭚,㒸,⿵𡶔𡭕}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
[[File:歲-oracle-2.svg|thumb|100px|Uncommon instance of {{m-self|zh|歲}} in the [[oracle bone script]] showing the two {{lang|zh|止}} components.]]
{{Han compound|步|戉|c1=s|c2=p|ls=psc}} to indicate the passing of time as "movement". Hence, the original version was close to [[𢧁]]. In addition to {{zh-l|*戉}}, various components such as {{zh-l|*月|gloss=moon; month}} used to be present, sometimes as simple as two dots.

The current form derives from the {{w|Qin (state)|Qin}}-style handwriting of the late {{w|Warring States}} (with a full-width {{zh-l|*止}} on the top and a bottom-left {{zh-l|*撇}} stroke extending outward as in {{zh-l|*戊}} or {{zh-l|*戌}} instead of bending inward as in {{zh-l|*戉}}), which was also inherited by the [[clerical script]].

===Etymology===
A derivative of {{och-l|越|to pass over|id=2}} ({{zh-ref|Mei, 1979, 1992}}). Ultimately probably from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*ɢʷrat||to travel; to go through}}; compare {{cog|bo|སྐྱོད||to go}} ({{zh-ref|Mei, 1979, 1992}}; {{zh-ref|Gong Hwang-cherng, 2002}}; STEDT).

The functions of the ''*s-'' prefix and the ''*-s'' suffix are not clear. Possible explanations include:
* ''*s-'' as a [[directive]] prefix and ''*-s'' as a [[nominalizer]] ({{zh-ref|Mei, 1992}});
* ''*s-'' is an [[iterative]] prefix, literally "to pass on again" ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}});
* ''*s-'' (possibly with ''*-s'') as a [[nominalizer]] ({{zh-ref|Smith, 2012}}).

Alternatively, it may be derived from a word like {{och-l|圓|round; circle}} (< {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*wal||round; circular}}), literally "to start the circle/cycle again" ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Outside of Sino-Tibetan, this word has been compared to {{cog|th|ขวบ||year}}, which {{zh-ref|Bodman (1980)}} considers to be a loan from Chinese, as well as {{cog|map-pro|*kawaS||year; season; sky}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 2005}}).

Also see {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} and {{zh-ref|Smith (2012)}} for a discussion on the semantic development of this word, especially the connection between "Jupiter" and "year".

